1416
02:00:12,331 --> 02:00:13,452
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you, President.

1417
02:00:14,152 --> 02:00:18,515
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you so much, Bob for this whole presentation we really appreciate you.

1418
02:00:19,500 --> 02:00:22,363
[SPEAKER_00]: being here and walking us through so much content.

1419
02:00:22,583 --> 02:00:27,087
[SPEAKER_00]: I wanted to save my comments for the end just because I know you had a lot to get through.

1420
02:00:27,827 --> 02:00:41,439
[SPEAKER_00]: Just in closing, I think that conversations like this are really helpful for helping us get clear on what data we need and hopefully articulate that in a way that you and the administration can act on to make sure that we're actually in communication, not just passing notes.

1421
02:00:43,105 --> 02:00:48,129
[SPEAKER_00]: You know I think ultimately we're here to talk about what we need to see as counselors and based on the questions that we get from the community.

1422
02:00:48,149 --> 02:00:57,035
[SPEAKER_00]: You know kind of touching back on what were for me the highlights of your presentation spoke about you know i'm really interested in that year to date spend i'm interested in revenue forecasting.

1423
02:00:57,961 --> 02:01:02,502
[SPEAKER_00]: The snapshots are useful, but we need both sides of that coin, the snapshots and the trends.

1424
02:01:04,063 --> 02:01:09,524
[SPEAKER_00]: Residents do come to us to inquire about, quote unquote, where the community is headed, and we need the information to speak to that.

1425
02:01:10,104 --> 02:01:13,605
[SPEAKER_00]: Even the slide, like this final one that you're sharing, I think is very helpful.

1426
02:01:13,665 --> 02:01:15,186
[SPEAKER_00]: It has the touch points on major updates.

1427
02:01:15,226 --> 02:01:22,308
[SPEAKER_00]: It has a bit of forecasting, what's been budgeted, how deep we are into appropriations as a percentage of total budget at a relevant point in time.

1428
02:01:23,549 --> 02:01:32,835
[SPEAKER_00]: You know, comparing that to just looking back at the plan that we pass in June of each year, when we're looking for meaningful updates on how we're doing, this feels substantively different in a useful way.

1429
02:01:32,855 --> 02:01:38,739
[SPEAKER_00]: And I think that this could be really valuable, especially if these data points were comparative going back three or five years.

1430
02:01:39,720 --> 02:01:43,142
[SPEAKER_00]: But, you know, in either case, I think that this is the type of information that I've been really wanting.

1431
02:01:44,594 --> 02:01:57,447
[SPEAKER_00]: I think in terms of what we're asking for going forward I'm really glad that special revenue funds have been a part of this conversation alongside the general fund because I think you know if we're asking for context, seeing that whole pie chart is really is really necessary.

1432
02:01:59,318 --> 02:02:10,825
[SPEAKER_00]: you know, and I'm glad that we're getting to a point where we're able to better articulate why more specifically we're looking to see, and hopefully we can, you know, be working together to make sure that we're getting that information, even if it's not always as soon as possible.

1433
02:02:12,286 --> 02:02:18,849
[SPEAKER_00]: One of my main takeaways was, you know, building up your department, you know, making sure that we can be building up the finance department's capacity.

1434
02:02:19,550 --> 02:02:22,211
[SPEAKER_00]: Clearly there's some specific bottlenecks.

1435
02:02:22,572 --> 02:02:24,393
[SPEAKER_00]: I think that we all want to see them prioritized.

1436
02:02:25,673 --> 02:02:33,158
[SPEAKER_00]: You know, I hope that we can get to a point where we don't have to be self-censoring and what data we're asking for, you know, for ourselves and also for the community.

1437
02:02:33,979 --> 02:02:42,985
[SPEAKER_00]: And part of why we want this data broadly is so that we can know, you know, if we're not able to invest more aggressively in capacity like the finance department, you know, why is that?

1438
02:02:43,205 --> 02:02:45,346
[SPEAKER_00]: And how can we kind of be partners in addressing it?

1439
02:02:46,973 --> 02:02:51,676
[SPEAKER_00]: Obviously, there are a lot of issues orbiting this conversation like a comprehensive capital needs assessment.

1440
02:02:51,696 --> 02:02:52,957
[SPEAKER_00]: That's a piece too.

1441
02:02:52,997 --> 02:02:56,639
[SPEAKER_00]: I know it's outside the scope of this conversation and not just because we've been talking for two hours.

1442
02:02:58,440 --> 02:03:01,943
[SPEAKER_00]: But I think that, you know, overall, we're trying to build this up on a lot of different layers.

1443
02:03:03,003 --> 02:03:09,826
[SPEAKER_00]: what we can expect from our next budget season and the next one and a budget scenario and future planning that goes even farther than that.

1444
02:03:10,847 --> 02:03:13,808
[SPEAKER_00]: But conversations like this make me feel a lot more optimistic.

1445
02:03:14,568 --> 02:03:26,014
[SPEAKER_00]: And I think that this council wants to be able to know how to effectively voice support for in certain capacity where it needs to go in order to get the data that we're asking for, in order to make that data easier to come by.

1446
02:03:26,034 --> 02:03:28,975
[SPEAKER_00]: And hopefully, you know, as a corollary or as an accessory,

1447
02:03:29,375 --> 02:03:31,237
[SPEAKER_00]: articulating that long term needs assessment.

1448
02:03:32,458 --> 02:03:34,880
[SPEAKER_00]: That's like, you know, that very related but separate project.

1449
02:03:34,940 --> 02:03:36,341
[SPEAKER_00]: So thank you.

1450
02:03:36,361 --> 02:03:37,382
[SPEAKER_00]: I really appreciate that.

1451
02:03:37,422 --> 02:03:38,583
[SPEAKER_00]: Lots of takeaways from this.

1452
02:03:39,484 --> 02:03:44,148
[SPEAKER_00]: And thank you to my fellow counselors for their time.

